Adjusting forecast based on an apparent decrease in opposition polling numbers over the past month. Fidesz seems to have gained a little bit more of an advantage. Slowly but surely time is running out for major upheavals between now and the election.
Adjusting up as the coalition is holding together for now!

I don't know this situation at all, but it seems from the polling that Fidesz and United for Hungary are close in the polls, making a supermajority very unlikely. Still a slight advantage to Fidesz-KNDP, because of incumbency, plus the possibility Orban being able to use certain non-democratic means to influence the vote.

I hadn’t previously appreciated the extent of re-districting in favor of Fidesz. I’m also seeing a bit more negative sentiment by commentators regarding the “Rube Goldberg machine”-nature of the opposition, and the need for many moving parts to work together perfectly. There seems to have been more optimism that it could work a month or more back.

- There are 199 seats in the assembly. Per above, a majority is 100 seats, and a supermajority is 132 or more. - Fidesz has 133 seats currently. - In order to lose its supermajority, Fidesz will have to lose 2 seats. - In order to lose its majority, Fidesz will have to lose 34 seats.

"A generation of right-wing populists [] have risen to power in democracies like Turkey [] have coincided, at least at first, with periods of solid economic performance[]. They have remained in power by stoking nationalist passions and driving deep wedges into the electorate with hot-button cultural issues. Along the way, they have co-opted the news media and cowed opponents. Now these strongmen are grappling with rising prices, even as they face national elections within the next two years. In Hungary, where consumer prices are rising at their fastest pace since 2007, polls suggest that Mr. Orban will face his toughest election ever next year, as the cost of living and low wages become top concerns for voters. Voters in the nearby Czech Republic — which has faced rising inflation and soaring energy costs — just ousted Andrej Babis, the country’s billionaire right-wing populist prime minister, by a narrow margin. “Since the global financial recession, the global macroeconomic environment was a godsend to authoritarians,” said Daron Acemoglu, a professor of economics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who has studied the deterioration of democracies. “Essentially, with very low interest rates, it made many countries that had either weak democracies or semi-authoritarianism, or sometimes fully fledged authoritarianism, still attractive to foreign capital.” Their personalized approach to politics — and the fact that they have all been in office for years — makes it difficult for them to sidestep blame for the condition of the economy. At the same time, their brand of populism, which emphasizes nationalist rivalries and has been effective in the past, can seem out of touch to citizens whose standards of living are swiftly plummeting. Most observers think Mr. Erdogan has made a difficult situation much worse, with the prospect of more interest rate cuts and currency declines driving foreign investors to pull their money from Turkey. https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/13/business/inflation-turkey-brazil-hungary.html

To get a supermajority, Orban needs to equal or outperform last election. Given (a) a united opposition and (b) new surge in covid amongst a not-very-vaccinated population (c) various economic issues (see linked article) and (d) polling, I think that option is very unlikely. I also don't think Hungary is quite at the stage where Orban could easily just write his own result (Freedom House has Hungary as "partly free" currently).

The probability of Fidesz losing its majority seems higher now than ever before since Orban came to power (double-digit percentages!). The opposition and Fidesz are widely reported to be neck-in-neck in recent polling. Still, Orban has a lot of possibilities to make elections less than completely “free and fair”, so I’m assessing far less than even odds that the opposition will prevail.
